    <br />

    
    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Development and Validation of Analytical Techniques for Quantitative Estimation of Some Antihypertensive Drugs</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Lakshmi Sivasubramanian</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">QUANTITATIVE ESTIMATION<br />ANTIHYPERTENSIVE</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Mar-2011 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0021</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">The present study describes the development of a novel analytical
approach that can reduce by 80-fold the consumption of organic solvents. A
group of ten antihypertensive drugs were chosen for the study. The
applicability of H-Point Standard Addition Method (HPSAM) to resolving
overlapping spectra corresponding to different combinations of
antihypertensives were verified. The results show that HPSAM is suitable for
the simultaneous estimation of Irbesartan with Hydrochlorothiazide and
Valsartan with Hydrochlorothiazide in aqueous media. The proposed method
has been applied to the simultaneous determination of Hydrochlorothiazide in
the presence of Irbesartan or Valsartan in some synthetic samples and
formulations.
A new HPSAM is proposed for the resolution of ternary mixtures
which is not reported by earlier workers. The proposed method involves
identification of three suitable wavelengths and absorption correction steps.
The method calculates the analyte concentration from spectral data at two
wavelengths where the two species selected as interferents present the same
absorbance relationship. The proposed novel method was applied successfully
to the simultaneous determination of mixtures of Irbesartan,
Hydrochlorothiazide and Telmisartan, Ramipril, Hydrochlorothiazide and
v
telmisartan and the mixture of Losartan potassium, Hydrochlorothiazide and
Amlodipine besylate. Accuracy and reproducibility of the method on various
amounts of drugs were evaluated in their ternary mixtures. To investigate the
selectivity of the method and to ensure that no serious interferences were
observed, the determination of antihypertensives was studied from the
formulation. This method utilizes the greatest advantage of HPSAM that it
can remove the error resulting from the presence of an interferent. So,
HPSAM can determine two or three drugs simultaneously.
A new chemometrics assisted spectrophotometric methods for
simultaneous determination of binary and ternary mixtures were reported. The
UV absorption spectra of the studied drugs, in the range of 200-350 nm
showed a considerable degree of spectral overlapping. Resolution of the
mixture has been accomplished by using Partial Least Squares (PLS) and
Principal Component Regression (PCR) methods. The proposed methods
were applied for the determination of two or three drugs in laboratory
prepared mixtures. Good percentage recoveries and proper statistical data
obtained with both the laboratory prepared mixtures and commercial tablets
proved the suitability and efficiency of the proposed procedures for routine
analysis and quality control purposes with quite satisfactory precision. The
PLS and PCR methods were extended for first derivative and second
derivative spectra of the drugs under study.
vi
A simple reverse-phased high performance liquid chromatographic
(RP-HPLC) method has been developed and validated for simultaneous
determination of Irbesartan, Losartan, Valsartan, Telmisartan and
Hydrochlorothiazide in synthetic samples, formulations and biological
samples. The compounds were separated on ODS analytical column with a
mixture of acetonitrile and water in the ratio 70:30 v/v. UV detection was
performed at 210 nm. The drugs were resolved with gradient elution system
with the run time of 20 min. The method was validated for accuracy,
precision, specificity, linearity and sensitivity. The developed and validated
method was successfully applied for quantitative analysis of studied drugs
from formulations. Total chromatographic analysis time was 20 min with
Telmisartan, Hydrochlorothiazide, Losartan, Irbesartan and Valsartan eluting
with retention times 4.71, 5.68, 7.06, 9.56 and 15.39 min respectively.
Calibration plots were linear over the range of 50-250 μg/ml for
Hydrochlorothiazide and 25-125 μg/ml for other drugs. Recovery was in the
range of 97-103% with the relative standard deviation of less than 2% for all
the drugs. The high percentage recovery and low coefficient of variation
confirm the suitability of the method for simultaneous analysis of all five
antihypertensives.
A new simple, accurate and precise high performance thin layer
chromatographic (HPTLC) method has been established for simultaneous
analysis of Irbesartan, Telmisartan, Hydrochlorothiazide and Ramipril in
synthetic samples and formulations. Standard and sample solutions of the
vii
studied drugs were applied to precoated silica gel G 60 F254 HPTLC plates
and the plates were developed with acetonitrile:toluene:methanol:formic acid
in the ratio 8:10:2:0.6 v/v/v/v as mobile phase. Detection and evaluation of
chromatograms was performed densitometrically at 210 nm. The retention
factors were 0.35, 0.42, 0.54 and 0.60 for Ramipril, Telmisartan,
Hydrochlorothiazide and Irbesartan respectively. The linear range was 500-
2500 ng/spot for Hydrochlorothiazide and 250-1250 ng/spot for other drugs
with the correlation coefficient greater than 0.9990. The method was validated
and successfully used for the analysis of drugs in tablets.
The approach described herein is of great practical value in
pharmaceutical analysis as it reduces the exposure of analysts to toxic effects
of organic solvents, lowers the cost by 50-fold, and it has a high throughput
property. Although the approach is validated for few antihypertensives, the
same methodology can be used for any other drugs possessing the ideal
properties.</td></tr>
